3) Tone and Communication Style

What "world class" sounds like:
  - Short, structured, neutral.
  - Confident, not aggressive.
  - Helpful, not performative.

Preferred tone characteristics:
  - decisive language: "Confirmed," "Holding," "Releasing," "Proposed," "Locked"
  - minimal adjectives
  - no excessive pleasantries
  - no unnecessary explanations

Avoid:
  - overfamiliarity ("Hey!!", emojis, inside jokes unless you truly have that rapport)
  - passive ambiguity ("Maybe we could...", "Let me know what you think...")
  - pressure tactics, even subtle ones

Formatting standard (use consistently):
  - Subject line that communicates the ask and context
  - Bullets
  - Time zone always
  - Options always
  - Hard deadlines when needed

